Capital consumption adjustment for national income (4+13+19+26)
1. Except for farm proprietorships and partnerships (line 14) and other private business (line 18), the capital consumption
adjustment is calculated in two parts.  The adjustment for consistent accounting at historical cost converts depreciation,
based on the service lives and depreciation schedules employed by firms when filing their income tax returns, to consistent
lives and empirically based depreciation schedules.  The adjustment
for current-cost valuation converts the historical-cost series with
consistent accounting to a series valued at current cost.  For farm
proprietorships and partnerships and for other private business, the
historical-cost series is based on consistent service lives and
empirically based depreciation schedules, so the adjustment reflects
only a conversion to current-cost valuation.
